        "Create a six-column xylem vs phloem comparison table. Rows: tracheid, vessel element, sieve tube element, companion cell. Columns: (1) tissue (xylem/phloem); (2) living or dead at maturity; (3) end wall structure; (4) wall characteristics; (5) primary function; (6) unique identifying feature. Use this as a self-test before every examination.",
        "Create a four-column dicot vs monocot comparison table for root, stem, and leaf. Rows: root (vascular arrangement), stem (bundle arrangement, secondary growth), leaf (venation). Columns: (1) organ; (2) dicot feature; (3) monocot feature; (4) functional consequence of the difference. This table encodes all the comparative anatomy needed for identification questions.",
        "Create a comparison table of leaf adaptations for four environments: sun, shade, xerophyte, hydrophyte. Rows: cuticle thickness, stomatal position, stomatal density, mesophyll organisation, intercellular air spaces, water storage tissue. For each cell, write the expected feature. Use this to predict unknowns: cover the environment column and reconstruct it from anatomical features.",
        "Create a transport comparison table for xylem and phloem with rows for: cell types, living state, transported materials, direction, driving force, energy requirement, one anatomical feature that confirms the mechanism. Fill every cell with a maximum of ten words. This forces precise, concise knowledge rather than vague descriptions."
